+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0142kghwF3ZFd4SEuATrRovE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The `meetInTheMiddle` approach doesn't actually reduce complexity since pivot variables depend on all free variables. I need a real algorithm for minimum weight solution over GF(2) null space.\n\n**Key insight**: The minimum-weight codeword problem is NP-hard in general, but for small number of lights vs buttons (N ≤ 40 lights, M ≤ 40 buttons), the null space dimension can be at most M - rank ≤ M - 0 = 40. \n\nHowever, the actual worst case is determined by the **rank** of the button matrix. With 40 lights, rank ≤ 40. So free vars = M - rank ≥ M - 40. If M = 40, rank can be at most 40, so free vars ≥ 0. The bad case is when many buttons are redundant.\n\nA proper approach for min-weight codeword with 40-bit vectors: use the structure. The particular solution + null space gives all solutions. To find minimum weight, we can use an iterative beam search, or since we need lexicographic tie-breaking, use a BFS by weight.\n\nActually, there's a better approach. The null space has dimension d ≤ 40. We have d basis vectors. The minimum-weight solution in the coset is equivalent to finding a subset of null-space basis vectors to XOR with the particular solution that minimizes weight.\n\nFor d ≤ 20, enumerate 2^d → 2^20 = 1M, fast.  \nFor d > 20, use meet-in-the-middle **on the null space basis vectors** (not the free variable assignments). This is the classic technique.\n\nFor the actual meet-in-the-middle on null space:\n- Split d basis vectors into two halves of d/2 each\n- First half: enumerate 2^(d/2) combinations, store as (xor_value → best candidate)\n- Second half: enumerate 2^(d/2) combinations, for each compute partial XOR with particular solution and look up complement in first half\n\nBut this still requires combining, and for minimum weight it's not straightforward without enumerating all pairs. The key is that weight(A XOR B) is not simply decomposable.\n\nThe correct meet-in-the-middle for minimum Hamming weight:\n- Group all 2^(d/2) \"first-half\" vectors into a table by bit pattern\n- For each \"second-half\" vector, XOR with particular solution → need complement from first half\n- This works if we store popcount and can search for minimum total popcount pairs\n\nThis is O(2^(d/2) log(2^(d/2))) per half = O(2^20 * 20) = ~20M, fast.\n\nLet me implement the proper meet-in-the-middle:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1098,"cache_read_input_tokens":46205,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1098},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"650425f4-6a8c-484a-b0c6-6795964399da","uuid":"8eef8620-089a-4a8f-9af5-dadc7c92fbec"}
